Lung cancer is the leading cause if cancer death worldwide.

Small cell lung cancer:
Typical patient is a male older than 70, current or previous smoker.
SCLC is defined by light microscopy as "tumour with cells which uave a dmall size , scant cytoplasmic, absent of inconspicuous nucleoli".
90% express TTF-1 which ?can be used for identification.
Caused by mutations in TP53 and RB1 genes.

Occur in central airways causing symptoms within weeks.
Commonly associated eith paraneoplastic syndromes.

  1. SIADH - 15 - 40%
  2. Ectopic cushings 5%
  3. Lambert eaton syndrome - 3%
    I'm>[!INFO] Definition of Paraneoplastic syndromes
  • Lung cancer is the most common cancer associated with neurologic syndromes.
  • Mainly associated with Small Cell Lung Cancer (SCLC).
  • Immune mediated.
    1. Paraneoplastic LEMS is invariably associated with SCLC.

The clinical syndrome of MG can w caused by various types of antibodies which block transmission at the neuromuscular junction.

  • AChR - anti acetylcholine receptor antibodies

    • are IgG which damage the postsynaptic membrane and its receptors (via complementary mediated mechanisms)

  • anti Muscle specific kinase (anti musk) - antibodies agains the musk proteins ehich is rewuired for proper clustering of post synaptic acetyl choline receptors.

    • MuSK - less commonly found. (Muscle specific kinase antibody)

  • Immune complex mediated, small vessel vasculitis.
  • Prototype disease of "diffuse alveolar haemorrhage syndromes".
  • Diffuse alveolar haemorrhage syndromes consist of a triad of haemoptysis, anaemia and diffuse pulmonary infiltrates.
  • Respiratory symptoms may precede glomerulonephritis by weeks to months.
  • Mild to life threatening haemopsytis.
    Treatment: remove the antibodies by plasmapheresis and prevent recurrence with immunosuppression (prednisilone / cyclophosphamide)
    Prognosis: Recurrence is rare; earlier diagnosis -> less severe renal failure -> recovery; late diagnosis or significant renal impairment at presentation -> chronic kidney disease and dialysis requirement.

Diagnosis
  • ANCA positivity for the respective ANCA.
  • Renal biopsy is indicated:
    • Granulomas + in GPA, not in MPA.
    • mild focal segmenl glomerulonephritis up to diffuse necrotizng crescenase
Treatment of GPA and MPA

Immunosuppressive therapy is warranted in almost all patients with active GPA or MPA

Immunosuppressive therapy consists of induction phase and maintenance phase.

  • Eosinophilia+
  • Allergic rhinitis and asthma that's difficult to control.
  • p-ANCA positive. (=MPO ANCA)
    Systemic vasculitis develops later:

The most commonly involved organ is the lung, followed by the skin - UpToDate

  1. Tender subcutaneous nodules (half to 2/3 have skin involvement)
  2. Mononeuritis multiplex
  3. Kidneys - can cause rapidly progressing AKI with necrotizng glomerulonephritis (haematuria, proteinuria or normal ufr)
  • Responds well to steroids.

The American College of Rheumatology has produced criteria for the diagnosis of EGPA: asthma, eosinophilia, presence of mono-/polyneuropathy, flitting pulmonary infiltrates, paranasal sinus abnormalities and histological evidence of extravascular eosinophils - PassMedicine
